{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f865671d-9142-4119-840f-3d187fdc4127","content":"The best approach is `dotnet-trace` with the CPU profiling profile:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool (if not already in the container)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n**Tips for K8s:**\n- Copy the trace out with `kubectl cp <pod>:<path>/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace`\n- If you can't install tools in the container, use a [sidecar or ephemeral debug container](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-trace#collect-using-an-ephemeral-container) with the diagnostic tools pre-installed.\n- For very high CPU where managed tooling is unresponsive, consider `perf record` (Linux native) instead — it doesn't require the .NET diagnostic port.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"955d9f4f-c8dd-4a89-b5c7-e7ae6093c95b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostics/performance question - I can answer from knowledge without needing to search files.","outputTokens":348,"requestId":"6811:2EE789:C2D144:D05F03:6A0B00C6"},"id":"203fbfec-15b5-4163-980a-665e315f6a5d","timestamp":"2026-05-18T12:06:40.990Z","parentId":"95e63831-3cc3-42ee-a267-4fe02d87642b"}
